      <h3>Accreditation language to know</h3>
      <p>
        Use <strong>institutional accreditation</strong> when the accreditor reviews an entire
        college or university. Use <strong>programmatic accreditation</strong> when the accreditor
        reviews a specific program such as nursing, engineering, or counseling. Some schools highlight
        both because institutional accreditation and program accreditation serve different purposes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section id="how-to-use-these-acronyms">
      <h2>How to use these acronyms</h2>
      <p>
        When writing for a general audience, define the acronym on first mention and then use the
        short form afterward. That keeps the content readable while still making it searchable. For
        example, write “Bachelor of Science in Nursing (BSN)” the first time and “BSN” afterward.
      </p>
      <p>
        For SEO, the best approach is to place the acronym in an H2 or H3 heading, then add a short
        definition and a plain-English explanation. This improves scanability and gives each acronym
        a strong chance to rank independently in search results. It also makes the page easy to reuse
        as a hub or sitemap-style glossary.
      </p>
    </section>

